rary evidence-and explores how our constitutional structure, an evolving economy, and developments in procedural rules and litigation financing systems have moved us from expecting that lawsuits end in trial and judgments to expecting that they will end in settlements. Yeazell argues that today's system has in some ways overcome-albeit inconsistently-disparities between the rich and poor in access to civil justice. Once upon a time, might regularly triumphed over right. That is slightly less likely today-even though we continue to witness enormous disparities in wealth and power. The book concludes with an evaluation of recent changes and their possible consequences.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aActions and defenseszUnited States. 0aCivil procedurezUnited States. 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)xEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aClass actions (Civil procedure)zUnited States. 4acivil. 4adiscovery. 4ajudgment. 4alawsuit. 4alawyers. 4alegal profession. 4alitigation finance. 4alitigation. 4asettlement. 4atrial. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226546421423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226546421.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles